ater used for preheating the mash tun into the 20l kettle','',0,9,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(174,'test@example.com','15AG10i11','Fill the mash tun with  ...mash_liquid...L of water heated to ...strike_temp_5...C.','',0,9,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(175,'test@example.com','15AG10i11','Set aside 1.7L of boiling water and 1.7L of cold water which may optionally may be used for adjustment of temperature/consistency','',0,9,2,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(176,'test@example.com','15AG10i11','Dough in the grain','',0,10,-1,'The temperature for mashing is important high temperatures will lead to extraction of tannins, low temperatures will not provide efficient conversion. Lower temperature conversion - around 64-66.6C  will take longer but will produce a more complete conversion of complex starches to sugars resulting in more fermentation and a clean, lighter tasting beer. A high temperature conversion of 68.5-70 C will result in less starch conversion leaving a beer with more unfermentable dextrines. This will create a beer with a full body and flavor. Middle mash temperatures  67.69 C will result in medium bodied beers.  The consistency of the mixture should be resemble porridge. (Note: this is still subject to refining in the past this was calculated with a ratio of 1.25 but recipes will be at least 1.5','[\"mash_setup.png\"]','The Temperature of the Grain Bed should remain below 75degC throughout.','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(177,'test@example.com','15AG10i11','With the temperature of the mash liquid at ...strike_temp...C stir in the grain.','',0,10,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(178,'test@example.com','15AG10i11','The aim is to mash at a temperature of ...target_mash_temp...C','',0,10,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(179,'test@example.com','15AG10i11','Cover and set aside for 60 minutes.','',0,10,2,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(180,'test@example.com','15AG10i11','If after a few minutes the temperature difference 