 higher than the mash tun with the sparge arm assembled. The brewing kettle is positoned the lowest.','[\"sterilise_setup1.png\"]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(593,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Setup the equipment as pictured','',0,9,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(594,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Plug in the ATC-800+ temperature controller and set to ...strike_temp_5...degC. Ensure the supply is off and then connect the power leads from the controller to the elements on the HLT.','',0,9,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(595,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Ensure the Internal Latstock is connected to the hlt and the sparge arm is connected to the tap.','',0,9,2,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(596,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Ensure the Tap and Scavenger tube are connected to the Mash Tun, feed the temperature probe for the thermometer through the side of the lauten tun.','',0,9,3,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(597,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Treat Mash Water / Begin heating mash water','',0,10,-1,'Fill the HLT with ...mash_liquid_6...L of water for the mash and heat to strike temp + 5 deg. The strike temperature takes account of the cold grain absorbing heat.','[\"treatwater.png\"]','Do not turn on the temperature controller until the elements in the kettle are covered with water.','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(598,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Fill the hot liquor tank with ...mash_liquid_6...L of water for the mash','',0,10,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(599,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','If not using bottled water for the Mash Liquid crush half a Campden tablet into the water and leave for 5 minutes. Leave a further 5 minutes and there stir well.','',0,10,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(600,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Begin heating the mash liquid to ...strike_temp_5...C, continue with other steps in the background.','',0,10,2,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(601,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Get Ready to Mash','',0,11,-1,'During the mash the complex starches into simple sugars suitable for fermentation. The mash-tun is pre-heated during this step to minimise the heat lost to the cold mashtun. During mashing temperature control is important but an insulated mash tun will not change significantly over an hour.  ','[\"mash.png\"]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'grainqty',1,0,'[]'),(602,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Boil 1.5L of tap water and add to the mash tun, add the lid to the mash tun','',0,11,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(603,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Add 2 teaspoons of burton water salts to the grain.','',0,11,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(604,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Fill the mash tun with mash liquid','',0,12,-1,'Fill the mashtun with the mash liquor in order the water is to ...strike_temp...C (Strike Temp ...strike_temp...C). The water in the HLT should be heated to 5degC higher than strke temp to account for some losses while transferring the liquid, however the temperature should be monitored.','[]','If the grain temperature is not between 15-20 degC then the calculations should be re-run to provide a hotter/colder strike temp.','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(605,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Discard the water used for preheating the mash tun into the 20l kettle','',0,12,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(606,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Fill the mash tun with  ...mash_liquid...L of water heated to ...strike_temp_5...C.','',0,12,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(607,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Set aside 1.7L of boiling water and 1.7L of cold water which may optionally may be used for adjustment of temperature/consistency','',0,12,2,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(608,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Dough in the grain','',0,13,-1,'The temperature for mashing is important high temperatures will lead to extraction of tannins, low temperatures will not provide efficient conversion. Lower temperature conversion - around 64-66.6C  will take longer but will produce a more complete conversion of complex starches to sugars resulting in more fermentation and a clean, lighter tasting beer. A high temperature conversion of 68.5-70 C will result in less starch conversion leaving a beer with more unfermentable dextrines. This will create a beer with a full body and flavor. Middle mash temperatures  67.69 C will result in medium bodied beers.  The consistency of the mixture should be resemble porridge. (Note: this is still subject to refining in the past this was calculated with a ratio of 1.25 but recipes will be at least 1.5','[\"dough.png\"]','The Temperature of the Grain Bed should remain below 75degC throughout.','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(609,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','With the temperature of the mash liquid at ...strike_temp...C stir in the grain.','',0,13,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(610,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','The aim is to mash at a temperature of ...target_mash_temp...C','',0,13,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(611,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Cover and set aside for 60 minutes.','',0,13,2,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(612,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','If after a few minutes the temperature difference is +/- 3degC of the ...target_mash_temp...C target then a temperature adjustment may be carried out with care.','',0,13,3,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(613,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Fill the HLT and begin heating','',0,14,-1,'Fill the HLT with sparge water, there will be some water left in the HLT after taking out the mash water. The sparge water is expected to take around ...sparge_heating_time... minutes to heat. Note: this process assumes bottled/britta filtered water will be used for this step.','[]','The HLT is constructed with standard kettle elements, therefore it is advisable to alternate between the elements 3 or 4 times during the heating. The temperature controller should only power one kettle element at any time.','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(614,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Fill the HLT so that it contains ...sparge_water... L','',0,14,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(615,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Add citric acid (half a teaspoon) to the sparge water and stir.','',0,14,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(616,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Begin heating the sparge water to ...sparge_temp...C','',0,14,2,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(617,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Sterilise Equipment','',0,15,-1,'It is important throughout the brew day to keep any equipment which will come into contact with the wort post-boil sterilised. Equipment used before the boil does not need to be sterilised but does need to be clean','[\"sterilise1step.png\"]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(618,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Fill the fermentation bin with 10 litres of warm water and 2 tsp of sterilising powder.','',0,15,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(619,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Ensure fermentation bin is fully sterilised with equipment, after 10 minutes of sterilising equipment place equipment in the small storage stockport.','',0,15,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(620,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Ensure a \'filter\' is added to the back of the fermentation bin tap','',0,15,2,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(621,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Ensure all the feremntation bin has been sterilised and empty solution into the small stock pot.','',0,15,3,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(622,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Rinse Equipment','',0,16,-1,'Rinse Equipment in the same way as sterilising, equipment should be rinsed with 25 litres of cold water.','[]','Be careful to monitor the temperature during the mash, if the mash tun is well insulated it may be that the temperature rises not falls.','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(623,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Assemble Sparge Setup and begin Recirculation','',0,17,-1,'Once the sparge water is at the correct temperature ...sparge_temp...C AND the mash duration has completedthe sparge setup can be setup. During this step the cloudy wort with bits of grain will drained leading to a natural grain filter forming.','[\"spargesetup.png\"]','Set the thermometer to alarm if the temperature is higher than 71deg. If it is then lid should be lifted to reduce the heat.','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(624,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Take off the lid from the mash tun and assemble the sparge arm','',0,17,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',0,0,'[]'),(625,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Allow up to 6 litres of wort to drain from the mash tun into the kettle, the wort should be carefully added back to the top of the lauter tun trying to ensure minimal disturbance.','',0,17,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(626,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Start Fly Sparging','',0,18,-1,'Sparging will drain the sugar from the grain providing us with wort. The process of sparging should be carried out slowly. The temperature of the gain bed will be raised during this proess (note there is no instant change of temperature). The grain bed should stay below 76 deg C. We need to aim for a boil volume of ...boil_vol...L. Wort should be drained and held in the fermentation bin until the end of sparging','[\"dosparge.png\"]','Note: the maximum boil volume supported is ...maxBoilVoulme...L (14L and 12L)','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(627,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Begin draining the wort from the mash tun into the jerry can, and start allowing water to slwoly drain from the HLT. As the temperature of the grain bed raises start to maintain a headspace above the top of the grain. As the jerry can fills empty into the','',0,18,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(628,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','After the sparge volume is reached or the gravity of the runoff is below 1.006 then stop sparging. Transfer 14L of wort into the 20L kettle and 12L into the 15L kettle. Leftover wort should be left aside','',0,18,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(629,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Dynamic Recipe Adjustment','',0,19,-1,'If the mash was particularly efficent/inefficient it may be desirarble to top up fermentables, dilute wort, increase/decrease hop quantities. The target post-mash/pre-boil gravity is ...pretopup_post_mash_og... (post-boil grain ...pretopup_estimated_gravity_grain..., total post-boil gravity ...estimated_og...). The target wort volume required is ...boil_vol...L. The gravity quotes here takes account of later topup of ...topupvol...L','[\"sighttube.png\"]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'dynamicrecipeadjustment',1,0,'[]'),(630,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Bring the Wort to the boil','',0,20,-1,'Boiling the wort extracts bitterness and aroma from the hops, driving off unwanted volatile components, coagulates proteins,  and sanitising the wort for fermentation. Remember the wort will reach a roiling boil and have hop additions therefore don\'t over fill the boilers. A topup of ...topupvol...L should be set aside until the end of the boil.','[\"boil.png\"]','Use thermometer alarm to determine when the wort has reached a boil.','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(631,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Start boiling the 20L Kettle','',0,20,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(632,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','After 15 minutes start boiling the 15L Kettle','',0,20,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(633,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Turn on the fridge with ATC Control to 20 degC','',0,20,2,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(634,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Measure the original gravity of the wort. It is expected that the pre-boil gravity without adjunct is ....pretopup_post_mash_og... and with adjuncts added ...pre_boil_gravity...)','',0,20,3,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(635,'test@example.com','19AG16i17','Measure the preboil/pretopup volume ...boil_vol...','',0,20,4,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(636,'test@example.com','19AG