sh.','[]','Be careful to monitor the temperature during the mash, if the mash tun is well insulated it may be that the temperature rises not falls. Temperature must not rise above 70C. High temperautere 68.5-70C results in more unfermentables, 67-68.5 will result in','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(779,'test@example.com','20AG17i18','Turn on the fridge with ATC Control to 20 degC','',0,17,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(780,'test@example.com','20AG17i18','Assemble Sparge Setup and begin Recirculation','',0,18,-1,'Once the sparge water is at the correct temperature ...sparge_temp...C AND the mash duration has completedthe sparge setup can be setup. During this step the cloudy wort with bits of grain will drained leading to a natural grain filter forming.','[\"spargesetup.png\"]','Set the thermometer to alarm if the temperature is higher than 71deg. If it is then lid should be lifted to reduce the heat.','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(781,'test@example.com','20AG17i18','Take off the lid from the mash tun and assemble the sparge arm','',0,18,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',0,0,'[]'),(782,'test@example.com','20AG17i18','Allow up to 6 litres of wort to drain from the mash tun into the kettle, the wort should be carefully added back to the top of the lauter tun trying to ensure minimal disturbance.','',0,18,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(783,'test@example.com','20AG17i18','Start Fly Sparging','',0,19,-1,'Sparging will drain the sugar from the grain providing us with wort. The process of sparging should be carried out slowly. The temperature of the gain bed will be raised during this proess (note there is no instant change of temperature). The grain bed should stay below 76 deg C. Our first sparge will provide the first wort to progress with boiling early.','[\"dosparge.png\"]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(784,'test@example.com','20AG17i18','Start Boiling the Wort [1]','',0,20,-1,'Boiling the wort drives off unwanted volatile components, coagulates proteins,  and sanitising the wort for fermentation. The first boil should be ...kettle1volume...L of wort. We are aiming for a gravity of ...kettle1preboilgravity...','[\"boil.png\"]','Use thermometer alarm to determine when the wort has reached a boil.','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(785,'test@example.com','20AG17i18','Start boiling the wort.','',0,20,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',0,0,'[]'),(786,'test@example.com','20AG17i18','Continue fly sparging','',0,21,-1,'Contiue the process of sparging. The temperature of the gain bed will be raised during this proess (note there is no instant change of temperature). The grain bed should stay below 76 deg C. We need to aim for a boil volume of ...boil_vol...L. Wort should be drained and held in the fermentation bin until the end of sparging','[\"dosparge.png\"]','Note: the maximum boil volume supported is ...maxBoilVoulme...L (14L and 12L)','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(787,'test@example.com','20AG17i18','Collect ...kettle2volume... in the second kettle.','',0,21,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(788,'test@example.com','20AG17i18','Collect ...kettle3volume... in the jerry for use later in the process. Pay careful attention to the gravity of teh sparge.','',0,21,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(789,'test@example.com','20AG17i18','Start Boiling the Wort [2]','',0,22,-1,'Boiling the wort extracts bitterness and aroma from the hops, driving off unwanted volatile components, coagulates proteins,  and sanitising the wort for fermentation. The second boil should be ...kettle2volume...L of wort. We are aiming for a gravity of ...kettle2preboilgravity...','[\"boil.png\"]','Use thermometer alarm to determine when the wort has reached a boil.','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(790,'test@example.com','20AG17i18','Start boiling the wort.','',0,22,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',0,0,'[]'),(791,'test@example.com','20AG17i18','Dynamic Recipe Adjustment','',0,23,-1,'If the mash was particularly efficent/inefficient it may be desirarble to top up fermentables, dil