,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1513,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Fill the mash tun with  ...mash_liquid...L of water heated to ...strike_temp_5...C.','',0,12,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1514,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Set aside 1.7L of boiling water and 1.7L of cold water which may optionally may be used for adjustment of temperature/consistency','',0,12,2,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1515,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Dough in the grain','',0,13,-1,'The temperature for mashing is important high temperatures will lead to extraction of tannins, low temperatures will not provide efficient conversion. Lower temperature conversion - around 64-66.6C  will take longer but will produce a more complete conversion of complex starches to sugars resulting in more fermentation and a clean, lighter tasting beer. A high temperature conversion of 68.5-70 C will result in less starch conversion leaving a beer with more unfermentable dextrines. This will create a beer with a full body and flavor. Middle mash temperatures  67.69 C will result in medium bodied beers.  The consistency of the mixture should be resemble porridge. (Note: this is still subject to refining in the past this was calculated with a ratio of 1.25 but recipes will be at least 1.5','[\"dough.png\"]','The Temperature of the Grain Bed should remain below 75degC throughout.','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1516,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','With the temperature of the mash liquid at ...strike_temp...C stir in the grain.','',0,13,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1517,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','The aim is to mash at a temperature of ...target_mash_temp...C','',0,13,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1518,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Cover and set aside for 60 minutes.','',0,13,2,'','[]','','a',3600,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1519,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','If after a few minutes the temperature difference is +/- 3degC of the ...target_mash_temp...C target then a temperature adjustment may be carried out with care.','',0,13,3,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1520,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Fill the HLT and begin heating','',0,14,-1,'Fill the HLT with sparge water, there will be some water left in the HLT after taking out the mash water. The sparge water is expected to take around ...sparge_heating_time... minutes to heat. Note: this process assumes bottled/britta filtered water will be used for this step.','[]','The HLT is constructed with standard kettle elements, therefore it is advisable to alternate between the elements 3 or 4 times during the heating. The temperature controller should only power one kettle element at any time.','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1521,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Fill the HLT so that it contains ...sparge_water... L','',0,14,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1522,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Add citric acid (half a teaspoon) to the sparge water and stir.','',0,14,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1523,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Begin heating the sparge water to ...sparge_temp...C','',0,14,2,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1524,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Sterilise Equipment','',0,15,-1,'It is important throughout the brew day to keep any equipment which will come into contact with the wort post-boil sterilised. Equipment used before the boil does not need to be sterilised but does need to be clean','[\"sterilise1step.png\"]','Be careful to monitor the temperature during the mash, if the mash tun is well insulated it may be that the temperature rises not falls. Temperature must not rise above 70C. High temperautere 68.5-70C results in more unfermentables, 67-68.5 will result in','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1525,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Fill the fermentation bin with 10 litres of warm water and 2 tsp of sterilising powder.','',0,15,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1526,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Ensure fermentation bin is fully sterilised with equipment, after 10 minutes of sterilising equipment place equipment in the small storage stockport.','',0,15,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1527,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Ensure a \'filter\' is added to the back of the fermentation bin tap','',0,15,2,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1528,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Ensure all the feremntation bin has been sterilised and empty solution into the small stock pot.','',0,15,3,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1529,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Rinse Equipment','',0,16,-1,'Rinse Equipment in the same way as sterilising, equipment should be rinsed with 25 litres of cold water.','[]','Be careful to monitor the temperature during the mash, if the mash tun is well insulated it may be that the temperature rises not falls. Temperature must not rise above 70C. High temperautere 68.5-70C results in more unfermentables, 67-68.5 will result in','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1530,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Monitor the Mash','',0,17,-1,'Monitor the temperature of the mash.','[]','Be careful to monitor the temperature during the mash, if the mash tun is well insulated it may be that the temperature rises not falls. Temperature must not rise above 70C. High temperautere 68.5-70C results in more unfermentables, 67-68.5 will result in','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1531,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Assemble Sparge Setup and begin Recirculation','',0,18,-1,'Once the sparge water is at the correct temperature ...sparge_temp...C AND the mash duration has completedthe sparge setup can be setup. During this step the cloudy wort with bits of grain will drained leading to a natural grain filter forming.','[\"spargesetup.png\"]','Set the thermometer to alarm if the temperature is higher than 71deg. If it is then lid should be lifted to reduce the heat.','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1532,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Take off the lid from the mash tun and assemble the sparge arm','',0,18,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',0,0,'[]'),(1533,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Allow up to 6 litres of wort to drain from the mash tun into the kettle, the wort should be carefully added back to the top of the lauter tun trying to ensure minimal disturbance.','',0,18,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1534,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Start Fly Sparging','',0,19,-1,'Sparging will drain the sugar from the grain providing us with wort. The process of sparging should be carried out slowly. The temperature of the gain bed will be raised during this proess (note there is no instant change of temperature). The grain bed should stay below 76 deg C. Our first sparge will provide the first wort to progress with boiling early.','[\"dosparge.png\"]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1535,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Start Boiling the Wort [1]','',0,20,-1,'Boiling the wort drives off unwanted volatile components, coagulates proteins,  and sanitising the wort for fermentation. The first boil should be ...kettle1volume...L of wort. We are aiming for a gravity of ...kettle1preboilgravity...','[\"boil.png\"]','Use thermometer alarm to determine when the wort has reached a boil.','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1536,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Start boiling the wort.','',0,20,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',0,0,'[]'),(1537,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Continue fly sparging','',0,21,-1,'Contiue the process of sparging. The temperature of the gain bed will be raised during this proess (note there is no instant change of temperature). The grain bed should stay below 76 deg C. We need to aim for a boil volume of ...boil_vol...L. Wort should be drained and held in the fermentation bin until the end of sparging','[\"dosparge.png\"]','Note: the maximum boil volume supported is 26L (14L and 12L)','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1538,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Collect ...kettle2volume... in the second kettle.','',0,21,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1539,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Collect ...kettle3volume... in the jerry for use later in the process. Pay careful attention to the gravity of teh sparge.','',0,21,1,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1540,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Start Boiling the Wort [2]','',0,22,-1,'Boiling the wort extracts bitterness and aroma from the hops, driving off unwanted volatile components, coagulates proteins,  and sanitising the wort for fermentation. The second boil should be ...kettle2volume...L of wort. We are aiming for a gravity of ...kettle2preboilgravity...','[\"boil.png\"]','Use thermometer alarm to determine when the wort has reached a boil.','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1541,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Start boiling the wort.','',0,22,0,'','[]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',0,0,'[]'),(1542,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Dynamic Recipe Adjustment','',0,23,-1,'If the mash was particularly efficent/inefficient it may be desirarble to top up fermentables, dilute wort, increase/decrease hop quantities. The target pre-boil gravity is ...preboil_gravity... (total post-boil gravity ...estimated_og...). The target wort volume required is ...boil_vol...L. The gravity quotes here takes account of later topup of ...topupvol...L. Estimated gravity post boil pre cooling is ...postboilprecoolgravity...','[\"sighttube.png\"]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1543,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Boil Kettle [1]','',0,24,-1,'Once the wort is at a rolling boil the adjuncts should be added and the lid should be left half covered. The first kettle will be boiled for 60 minutes. It is expected that the first kettle will loose ...kettle1evaporation...L due to evaporation. After 45 minutes adjuncts ','[\"boil.png\"]','','',0,0,0,0,0,'addadjuncts',1,0,'[]'),(1544,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','Start timer for 45 minutes.','',0,24,0,'','[]','','a',2700,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1545,'test@example.com','21AG18i19','After 15 minutes add the immersion chiller to the kettle, reset the timer for 15 minutes','',0,24,1,'','[]','','a',900,0,0,0,0,'',1,0,'[]'),(1546,'tes